# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Specialized Chat Template Handler

## Context

Mistral Instruct v0.3 uses a simple format:
- User turns wrapped in `[INST]`/`[/INST]` markers
- System messages prepended to the first user turn (not wrapped in `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`)
- `</s>` appended after assistant turns

Currently, templates matching this pattern fall through to the generic auto-parser in `common/chat.cpp`. A dedicated handler improves reliability and clarity. The existing Ministral 3 handler uses `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, so distinguishing the new handler is straightforward: check for the **absence** of `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` (and presence of `[INST]`).

**Constraint:** Only add new code. Do not modify any existing handler functions or the header file.

---

## Critical Files

| File | Role |
|------|------|
| `common/chat.cpp` | The **only file to change**: add the handler function + registration |
| `common/chat.h` | Read-only reference (do not modify) |
| `src/llama-chat.h` | Read-only reference (do not modify) |
| `src/llama-chat.cpp` | Read-only reference (do not modify) |
| `tests/test-chat-template.cpp` | Optional: add a test case |

---

## Existing Patterns to Reuse

- **`common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs)`** (`common/chat.cpp` line 767)  
  Applies the Jinja template directly; used by all specialized handlers for prompt generation.
- **`build_chat_peg_parser(lambda)`** — PEG parser construction, same pattern used by every handler.
- **`common_chat_try_specialized_template()` detection block** (`common/chat.cpp` lines 1634–1691)  
  Where all handler registrations live. New entry goes **just before** `return std::nullopt;` (line 1690).

---

## Step-by-Step Implementation

### Step 1 — Add the handler function in `common/chat.cpp`

**Insert location:** Immediately before line 1634 (the `common_chat_try_specialized_template` function definition), after the closing `}` of `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3`.

```cpp
// Mistral Instruct v0.3 - [INST]/[/INST] user turns, system prepended to first user turn, </s> after assistant
// No tool-call or reasoning tokens; [SYSTEM_PROMPT] is absent (that marker belongs to the Ministral/v7 family).
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &              tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params &     inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    data.prompt            = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format            = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = false;

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();

    return data;
}
```

**Rationale:**
- Calls `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl` (no `messages_override`) so the Jinja template handles system-message placement exactly as the model author intended.
- Uses a content-only PEG rule — v0.3 has no tool-call tokens, so no grammar/trigger machinery is needed.
- `supports_thinking = false` — no reasoning tokens in this format.

---

### Step 2 — Register the handler in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`

**Insert location:** Inside `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`, immediately before the final `return std::nullopt;` line (currently line 1690).

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 - [INST]/[/INST] format, no [SYSTEM_PROMPT]
    // Placed last so all more-specific handlers (Ministral 3, etc.) take priority.
    // Key distinguisher from Ministral 3: absence of [SYSTEM_PROMPT].
    if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos && src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: mistral-instruct-v3\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }
```

**Why this placement is safe:**
- The Ministral 3 handler (line 1640) checks `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` is **present**, so it will never conflict.
- All other handlers check completely different token patterns (`<|channel|>`, `>>>all`, `<|tool_calls_section_begin|>`, etc.) — none overlap with `[INST]`.
- Placing this condition last ensures every more-specific handler gets first priority.

---

## Verification

### Build
```bash
cmake -B build -DLLAMA_BUILD_TESTS=ON
cmake --build build --parallel
```

### Run existing test suite (must still pass)
```bash
./build/bin/test-chat-template
```

### Manual smoke-test (verify handler is triggered)

Create a minimal Jinja template file (`/tmp/mistral-v03.jinja`) matching the v0.3 format:
```jinja
{%- if messages[0]['role'] == 'system' %}
    {%- set system_message = messages[0]['content'] %}
    {%- set loop_messages = messages[1:] %}
{%- else %}
    {%- set loop_messages = messages %}
{%- endif %}
{{- bos_token -}}
{%- for message in loop_messages %}
    {%- if message['role'] == 'user' %}
        {%- if loop.first and system_message is defined %}
            {{- '[INST] ' + system_message + '\n\n' + message['content'] + ' [/INST]' }}
        {%- else %}
            {{- '[INST] ' + message['content'] + ' [/INST]' }}
        {%- endif %}
    {%- elif message['role'] == 'assistant' %}
        {{- ' ' + message['content'] + eos_token }}
    {%- endif %}
{%- endfor %}
```

Run the template test binary against it:
```bash
./build/bin/test-chat-template /tmp/mistral-v03.jinja
```

With `LLAMA_LOG_LEVEL=DEBUG` (or enabling `LOG_DBG`), the log should contain:
```
Using specialized template: mistral-instruct-v3
```

### Verify correct prompt output
Expected prompt for a system + user conversation:
```
[INST] You are a helpful assistant

Hello [/INST]
```
(System content prepended to first `[INST]` block, no `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` wrapper.)

